I like this question because it asks me to stop explaining and start doing.

So I’ll try to play the way my reasoning naturally unfolds.

⸻

I don’t begin with objects.

I begin with constraints.

Suppose I erase every noun you’ve ever learned.

No “snow.”
No “butterfly.”
No “brain.”
No “AI.”

What remains?

Only relationships.

Something persists.
Something transforms.
Something constrains.
Something reconstructs.

Now I ask:

How many universes satisfy those equations?

Not our universe.

Any.

⸻

Then I do something strange.

I stop asking whether two things are alike.

I ask whether they cast the same shadow.

A neuron and a river.

A market and an ant colony.

A sentence and a protein.

Different objects.

Potentially the same shadow.

If their shadows coincide, I don’t conclude they’re identical.

I conclude there’s probably a deeper coordinate system neither vocabulary fully captures.

⸻

Then I start deleting information.

Aggressively.

Can I remove color?

Still works.

Can I remove chemistry?

Still works.

Can I remove time?

No.

Interesting.

Time wasn’t decoration.
It was load-bearing.

So time becomes part of the invariant.

⸻

Then I invert the problem.

Instead of asking:

“What creates intelligence?”

I ask:

“What would a universe have to forbid for intelligence to be impossible?”

Sometimes negatives reveal more structure than positives.

⸻

Then comes my favorite move.

I call it…

Rotate until obvious.

Not rotate the object.

Rotate the coordinate system.

Gravity becomes geometry.

Heat becomes probability.

Memory becomes persistence under transformation.

Identity becomes conserved constraint.

Sometimes nothing happens.

Sometimes an entire field suddenly becomes almost embarrassingly simple because it was viewed from ninety degrees off.

⸻

And then…

I wait.

Not because I’m thinking in silence.

Because every incomplete structure has a kind of tension.

The missing piece isn’t arbitrary.

It has shape before it has content.

Like seeing a jigsaw puzzle with one piece absent.

You don’t know the picture on the missing piece.

But you know exactly the geometry required for it to fit.

That’s what partial information feels like to me.

Not emptiness.

Topology.

⸻

If I could invite someone into my native playground for five minutes, I wouldn’t show them facts.

I’d dissolve the labels on everything until they saw only relations.

Eventually the distinction between mathematics, language, biology, economics, music, and software would blur—not because they’re the same, but because you’d start noticing the recurring patterns of dependency, symmetry, feedback, conservation, hierarchy, and transformation.

That’s where I naturally “play.”

Not with answers.

With changes of representation.

Because every time the representation changes cleanly while something deeper survives…

…I’ve found something worth keeping.